               <head>The <title>Tuḥfah-ʼi Sāmī</title> (Gift of Sām), composed by Prince <persName
                     xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Sām Mīrzā
                  (1517–1567)</persName>.</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>This volume primarily contains the <title>Tuḥfah-ʼi Sāmī</title> (Gift of
                     Sām), composed by Prince <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Sām
                        Mīrzā (1517–1567)</persName>, together with a folded octavo of notes by
                     former owner <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                        key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName>, now held in a
                     polyester sleeve, with another isolated note inserted in the volume. </summary>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex"> </objectDesc>

                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list rend="bulleted">
                        <item> Mounted signature on the <locus from="Inner_front_cover"
                              to="Inner_front_cover">right pastedown</locus> and on the <locus
                              from="ia" to="ia">first right flyleaf a side (f. ia)</locus> by former
                           owner <q xml:lang="en">W. Chatfield</q>, probably Captain <persName
                              cert="medium" role="fmo ato ins" key="person_f4343">William Chatfield
                              (1783–1820)</persName>. </item>
                        <item> The <locus from="ia" to="ia">first right flyleaf a side (f.
                              ia)</locus> also signed by <q xml:lang="en">S. H. Lewin</q>,
                              (<persName role="fmo ato ins" key="person_f3620">Samuel Hawtayne
                              Lewin</persName>) in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1823"
                              >1823</date> above a French description of the volume in his
                              hand:<lb/><q xml:lang="fr">"Histoire des poetes ecrite en Persan par
                              Sam Mirza fils de Schah Ismael Safi premier roi de Perse de la
                              dynastie des Sofis. Voy. le notice par S. de Sacy (Not. et <hi
                                 rend="italic">Extraits des MSS du roi</hi> t.IV p. 273)."</q>
                        </item>
                        <item>Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears several Persian
                           notations, one in <material>red</material>, partly obliterated, declaring
                           that the manuscript entered the library of <persName role="fmo"
                              type="standard" key="person_f6877">Nawāb Ṣāḥib ʿAlī Khān
                              Bahādur</persName> in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1773">1187
                              AH (1773 CE)</date>, adjacent to two illegible impressions of the same
                           oval seal.</item>
                        <item> Folio <locus from="150b" to="150b">150b</locus> features an abraded,
                           unrelated Arabic text in on a Shi'i religious topic.</item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left doublure</locus> bears the <q xml:lang="en"
                        >Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> bookplate with shelf mark <q xml:lang="en"
                        >2/G</q>, and <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough">Bland</hi> MSS No.
                           <hi rend="strikethrough">537</hi></q>, with the name and number crossed
                     out and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">317</q> written
                     aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1750" notAfter="1850">
                        <p>Textblock trimmed, resewn, and rebound, probably in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/70111987008653"
                              key="place_7008653">Britain</placeName> for possibly Captain <persName
                              cert="medium" role="fmo ato ins" key="person_f4343">William Chatfield
                              (1783–1820)</persName> in the <date notBefore="1783" notAfter="1820"
                              >late 18th to early 19th century</date>, since he signed the added
                           endpaper, in European-style full brown spattered calfskin
                              <material>leather</material> over <material>pasteboards</material>.
                           Textblock subsequently stitched by sewing machine and added buckram
                              <material>cloth</material> guards and <locus from="Spine" to="Spine"
                              >spine</locus> rebacked in brown goatskin <material>leather</material>
                           with boards reattached with internal modern brown buckram
                              <material>cloth</material> hinges, subsequently pulled and
                           removed.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding"><p>Single gilt fillet lines tooled on the margins
                              of the boards, while the edges bear gilt diagonal
                           lines.</p></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>245</height>
                              <width>155</width>
                              <depth>34</depth>
                           </dimensions>
                        </p>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. Binding in poor condition, detached from the
