               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="medium" type="empire"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/6005089" key="place_6005089">Safavid
                        empire</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1570-03-10">22 Ramaz̤ān 977 AH (28
                        Feb. 1570 Julian/10 Mar. 1570 CE)</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>The manuscript entered the library of one <persName role="fmo"
                           key="person_f6877">Nawwāb Ṣāḥib ‘Alī Khān Bahādur</persName> in <origDate
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1773">1187 AH (1773 CE)</origDate> as per
                        an inscription on folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by an unknown owner, who described the volume
                        in French on the <locus from="ia" to="ia">first right flyleaf a side (f.
                           ia)</locus>, then one <q xml:lang="en">W. Chatfield</q>, probably
                           <persName role="fmo" cert="medium" key="person_f4343">William Chatfield
                           (1783–1820)</persName>. A nephew of Charles Chatfield (1751–1791),
                        Captain of the 1st Regiment Madras Light Native Cavalry and ultimately
                        Aide-de-Camp to Governor of Bengal William Hastings, he died at <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7570536" key="place_7570536"
                           >Kulladghee (Kalādgi)</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Presumably then inherited by his widow <persName cert="medium"
                           role="fmo">Caroline Augusta neé Duncombe Chatfield (1798–1880)</persName>
                        or daughter <persName>Mary Chatfield (1819-1853)</persName>, then brought to
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/70111987008653"
                           key="place_7008653">Britain</placeName> when they
                     returned.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Thereafter acquired in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1823"
                           >1823</date> from an unidentified source by <persName key="person_f3620"
                           role="fmo">Samuel Hawtayne Lewin (1795–1840)</persName>, one of the Six
                        Clerks of the Court of Chancery and Fellow of the Royal Asiatic Society, who
                        signed and described the volume on the <locus from="ia" to="ia">first right
                           flyleaf a side (f. ia)</locus>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Lewin's death, probably sold by his survivors to scholar
                           <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                           key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName> for his
                        library at Randalls Park, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735" key="place_7011735"
                           >Leatherhead</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                           >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866-06">June, 1866</date>, paid in two
                        instalments of £450 and £400, and then moved to <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                           Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
